Introduction¶

A new fast food chain has been witnessing rapid expansion over the past couple of years. They are now trying to optimise their supply chain to ensure that there is no shortage of ingredients. For this, they’ve tasked their data science team to come up with a model of their current pipeline that could predict the output of each food processing farm over the next few years. These predictions could further increase the efficiency of their current supply chain management systems. As a member of the data scientist team, you are expected to utilise your skills at machine learning to predict the output of the food processing farms for the next year. Facilitating this are 5 datasets that the company has provided access to you for:

  • train_data.csv, which contains the time series of each food processing farm along with that farm's ID, the ingredient type they are producing, and the yield in tonnes.
  • farm_data.csv, which contains the farm's ID, its year of founding and incorporation, the number of processing plants it has, the area of the farm (in $m^2$), the farm's parent company, and the farm's geographical location that has been anonymised.
  • train_weather.csv, which contains a time series of the weather at each farm from its location.

The other two datasets are test_data.csv and test_weather.csv. Right off the bat we can see that we have a multivariate time series modelling task on our hands, the difference from a normal version of this problem is the fact that we have multiple different time series to deal with in a multivariate fashion. The problem is therefore very involved, and the datasets are relatively large (combined, they size up to over 2GB). Keeping this in mind, the way the entire pipeline for this project has been structured is as follows:

FarmHack 2023 Data Pipeline

PostgreSQL Database¶

Owing to the size of the datasets, the iterative fashion of data wrangling, the necessity of joins, and the requirements that all of all this data management remain consistently and easily accessible, the decision was taken to setup a PostgreSQL database to store the datasets and manipulate them in a much, much easier fashion than through pure Python. The advantages of this method include, but are not limited to:

  • Direct database-style operations and querying.
  • Complete freedom from in-memory operations since databases are stored on disk.
  • Parallel operations with introspective query plans (contrasted against the GIL).
  • Extremely structured, straightforward and understandable approach to data management.
  • Dataset indexing for slightly increased performance during filter operations.
  • Very easy to prepare data for more advanced analytics and modelling.

The success, benefits and implications of this decision cannot be overstated. 90% of the entire data wrangling pipeline, from inspection through to data preparation for modelling was carried out purely in the PostgreSQL database, with the exception of advanced missing data imputation and the final modelling. The accompanying SQL script file along with a backup of the database (with reserved permissions) is contained within the archive this notebook should exist in. Finally, the database was stored on one highly capable and performant NVMe SSD.

Python Connection¶

Of course, not all operations could be carried out directly within the database for two reasons:

  • Although PostgreSQL ships with native support for direct within-database programming via C and procedural support via PL/Python, pointing the Python interpreter used to the one installed via Mamba was more work than necessary for the project.
  • Point (1) notwithstanding, using Python directly within the database - especially for ML/AI purposes - is a surefire way to completely shred the transistors on a storage device due to the repeated iterations involved. Such algorithms perform better when run from memory.

Therefore, the Python-PostgreSQL connector Psycopg2 was used to associate this Python session with the database instance to facilitate the absolute bare minimum amount of memory involvement. When an advanced operation was required, the database was connected to via Psycopg2 and queries were run that fetched only the bare minimum appropriate amount of data relevant to the job at hand. In most cases this was done iteratively, looping through different reasons for access; and functionally, so that the dataframe object doesn't have too long of a shelf life in-memory. The chosen workflow proved to be quite supportive of what the project required and might also be scalable to larger individual projects of similar natures.

Iterative Imputation¶

(Back to top)

This section coincides with parts 4 and 5 of the associated SQL script.

The goal here is to test, on a small representation of the entire dataset we have, the effects of iteratively imputing null values using an expectation-maximisation algorithm supplemented with Bayesian regression. The way EM works is - very generally - we have a given probability distribution of data but no knowledge of what the data represents in terms of its labels; in our case, we have missing values and we have no idea what they are, but we do have other data surrounding those points that we can use to infer what those values could be given a certain value. The way we infer this is usually Bayesian, and is based on the assumption that the source distribution of our data is a Gaussian:
$P(b | x_{i}) = \frac{P(x_{i} | b) \times P(b)}{P(x_{i} | b) \times P(b) + P(x_{i} | a) \times P(a)} \implies P(x_{i} | b) = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2 \pi \sigma_{b}^{2}}} \exp \lbrace -\frac{(x_{i} - \mu)^{2}}{2 \sigma_{b}^{2}} \rbrace$

What all of that math means is given a certain value $x_{i}$, we can identify what label it belongs to (or how much of an appropriate fit it is for a certain probability) by comparing it against the mean of the distribution we've already been given. What the Iterative Imputer is going to do (and what most EM imputation algorithms do, even the wicked-cool SVD one) is it's first going to fill nulls in a column with the column's mean, then regress one column against the others to obtain most "expected" values of the nulls in that column. It will replace the mean-imputed values with these new predicted values and proceed onto the next feature that was null, continuing in a round robin fashion until convergence is achieved or the maximum number of iterations has been reached. It's actually a really cool approach to imputation.

Imputation Test¶

(Back to top)

We'll start with a small, controlled set of data before expanding our operation into a loop over all locations we have. The way we script our code here will dictate how our future pipeline will turn out when we expand this over all locations, because a lot of copy/pasting will be involved. Like we noted in the SQL file, the most ideal solution here would have been to perform all of this directly within the database itself via PL/Python, which we also tried to do. Unfortunately, Postgres ships with its own Python interpreter that, if we want to change and point to Mamba's Python environment, would require an entire recompile of Postgres due to the single line change in a core configuration file. While computationally cheap for us, it's not temporally cheap. Importing pandas or numpy into the database directly is therefore not possible within the constraints of this problem, so we're doing it here.

Incredible, variance was preserved in a much more reasonable fashion. The reason we wanted a smaller decision space was because in our first attempt with this regressor, climate variability was completely destroyed (i.e. it blew up). For example, location 5410 before imputing had the following statistics, where d_* refers to the number of distinct values for that feature vector (also represented as a % of total):

We can clearly see the lack of variation across all the farms - every farm reporting from this location reports almost the same weather as every other farm, across all times of the day. Contrasted against the previous attempt's result, which was borderline within acceptable ranges, the newer approach is much, much cleaner. Interestingly enough, if we compare this regressor's performance against Julia's EM-SVD algorithm, we should notice that having only weather columns in play seriously narrows down the range of values we can end up with. Clearly weather interactions are being accounted for both ways. Now let's reappend our missing columns, fill forward cloudiness and move onto looping over this approach.

Full Imputation¶

(Back to top)

The way we structure this weighs heavily on how resource efficient we are. Just because we have copious amounts of memory and processing power available to us doesn't mean we should squander it all, on the contrary it would make the entire process much, much quicker if we streamline our consumption. To that end, we'll be doing this in a functional manner, trying to balance both execution speed and memory efficiency.

The main change we'll be making from our scripted sequence earlier is instead of using cursor.execute() for the main portion of our SQL query here, we'll be using extras.execute_values() from Psycopg2.extras, because [sic] "the current implementation of executemany() is (using an extremely charitable understatement) not particularly performing." The extra functions can be used to speed up the repeated execution of a statement against a set of parameters. By reducing the number of server roundtrips the performance can be orders of magnitude better than using executemany(). It's worth noting that an alternative utility which is also blazing fast is cursor.copy_to(), but that requires a little more nuanced memory management than what we probably need to do here.

We'll still be transacting the push by first creating a temporary table to hold our imputed dataframe, then deleting the rows in the original table and replacing them with the ones from said temporary table. This is, by far, the cleanest way to go about this whole ordeal. Given the approach we're taking, an index should only be created on this table once we're done.

Sources:

  • Psycopg2 Documentation; section Extras, subsection Fast Execution Helpers.
  • PostgreSQL Documentation; section COPY.
  • SO: Update a Postgres Table Column from a Pandas Dataframe.
  • SO: Pandas Update SQL.
  • SO: Bulk Update Postgres Column from Python Dataframe
  • SO: Psycopg2 Update Multiple Rows in a Table...
  • SO: Psycopg2 Update Multiple Columns on Multiple Rows...

def run_query(cursor, tables, location):
    cursor.execute(f"""
        SELECT *
        FROM {tables[0]}
        WHERE deidentified_location = '{location}';
    """)

    tmp_df = pd.DataFrame(
        cursor.fetchall(),
        columns = [titles[0] for titles in cursor.description]
    )

    return persist(
        cursor,
        impute(tmp_df),
        tables,
        location
    )
In [11]:
def impute(dataframe):
    # we're only imputing weather features; `cloudiness` is handled separately.
    imp_df = dataframe[
        ["temp_obs", "wind_direction", "dew_temp", "pressure_sea_level",
        "precipitation", "wind_speed"]
    ]

    # ignore columns that are 100% null
    imp_df = imp_df.iloc[:, ~imp_df.isnull().all(axis = "rows").values]

    # init the imputer and apply; we want a result in a dataframe
    iimp = IterativeImputer(
        imputation_order = "descending",
        random_state = 1337,
        min_value = list(imp_df.min(axis = "rows").values),
        max_value = list(imp_df.max(axis = "rows").values)
    )

    imp_df = pd.DataFrame(
        iimp.fit_transform(imp_df),
        columns = imp_df.columns
    )

    # save the original dataframe's column order for reindexing; after
    # imputing, overwrite the columns in `dataframe` with the imputed ones
    orig_cols = dataframe.columns
    dataframe.drop(imp_df.columns, axis = "columns", inplace = True)
    dataframe = pd.concat([dataframe, imp_df], axis = "columns")
    dataframe = dataframe.reindex(columns = orig_cols)

    # finally, if `cloudiness` isn't completely missing, impute that too
    if not dataframe["cloudiness"].isnull().all():
        dataframe["cloudiness"].fillna(method = "ffill", inplace = True)
        dataframe["cloudiness"].fillna(method = "bfill", inplace = True)

    return dataframe

def persist(cursor, dataframe, tables, location):
    vals = [tuple(x) for x in dataframe.to_numpy()]
    cols = ', '.join(list(dataframe.columns))
    dataframe = None

    # here we go
    cursor.execute("begin;")
    cursor.execute(f"""
        create temporary table feed on commit drop as
            select *
            from {tables[0]}
            with no data;
    """)

    extras.execute_values(
        cursor,
        f"insert into feed ({cols}) values %s",
        vals
    )
    vals = None
    cols = None

    cursor.execute(f"""
        delete from {tables[1]}
        where deidentified_location = '{location}';

        insert into {tables[1]} select * from feed;

        commit;
    """)

    print(f"committed {location} to {tables[1]}.")

    return 0

When we said we wanted a functional approach, we meant it in terms of one function calls another with the bare minimum information passing necessary. The first choice that should make the most difference in terms of keeping us within memory lines is the fact that our entrant function, run_query(), returns the final dataframe we want and calls the next appropriate function as a part of its return statement. The second choice that should supplement our first is repeatedly using local variables and mutating their values rather than indiscriminately assigning multiple different variables the values we need. For more information on how all of this is supposed to help, check out this blog post from Itamar Turner-Trauring (PythonSpeed).

As for why do we have tables as an argument, it's because instead of hardcoding this chain of operations for one table only (grand_merge, which is our training data), we've generalised it a little to accomodate operating with any pair of tables we choose. This also lets us use this chain for our testing data. Remember:

  • grand_merge ==> training dataset; spawns grand_impute ==> clean training dataset
  • test_merge ==> testing dataset; spawns test_impute ==> clean testing dataset

Which means our calling loop will do something like [run_query(cursor, ("grand_merge", "grand_impute"), loc) for loc in locations], then followed by [run_query(cursor, ("test_merge", "test_impute"), loc) for loc in locations].

Problem Deep Dive¶

(Back to top)

This section coincides with part 7 of the associated SQL script.

Now we get to the meat of our problem: how exactly do we go about forecasting farm yields for the year-ahead, for ~1,400 farms? There are a few absolutely brilliant, stellar, and seriously effective approaches that we can choose from; we're not talking about off-the-shelf models like a regular LSTM or GRU. We're talking about different kinds of architectures altogether, some of which are seriously wicked cool to be aware of. Before getting into what we're going to do, let's break down our problem into a more manageable mental representation:

  1. At the most granular level of information, we have per-farm year-prior yield data for each hour of the day. This constitutes a baseline amount, per farm, of $366 \times 24 = 8784$ timestamps (aka records), for 1,434 farms.
  2. The next level of aggregation is on the basis of farm location, where we have all of our 1,434 farms spread across 17 locations, with some locations having more farms than others.
  3. The next level above this is on the basis of the companies that own said farms, because each company can operate across multiple geographies; we have all our farms spread across different locations, operated by a total of 7 different styles of corporate topology.
  4. Finally, the highest level of aggregation is on the basis of ingredient produced by a farm, where we have each farm producing any of 4 different types of ingredients.

This seems too simple, so let's also account for the curveballs we had to deal with along the way: some farms are owned by one company across different locations (same farm_id and company, different locations), some farms are owned by different companies across the same location (same farm_id and location, different company), and some farms are owned by different companies across different locations. These scenarios are not unrealistic, for partnerships can cross geographies. We have also preprocessed and labelled our distributed categories appropriately. Finally, some farms produce only 1 of 4 ingredients while some produce all 4.

So we can see that we have multiple ways of slicing and dicing our data, but the end objective here is to predict, per farm and per hour, the year-ahead yield of that farm. After looking at how our data's spread out, we noticed a pretty hefty piece of the puzzle: weather across a location (obviously) won't change much - a fact which we leveraged quite well when imputing our missing values. A few supplemental observations and assumptions here are:

  • each farm's produce is independent from another farm's produce: farm A producing a yield amount of 60 units for a month doesn't impact farm B producing a yield amount of 25 units for a month. This is because we're assuming two things: one, the fast food chain maintains quotas of how much raw material is required for a certain amount of time; two, excess amount produced per farm is warehoused and stored. Therefore, all farms are assumed to operate in isolation without micromanagement and they all operate at maximum efficiency, given their climates.
  • the climate affecting the produce of farm A does not influence the produce of farm B; this assumption can also follow directly from the previous one. While practically speaking this is rather obtuse, within the working constraints we have for this problem it's a cleaner surface to work on if we assume the climate of South Africa doesn't influence the climate in Central Canada. This is compounded by the fact that we have anonymised locations, so we do not actually know whether our geographies are near to each other or spread out (MCAR).
  • the yield of one company's farms is independent from another company's yield. This is because each company can be using a different type of fertiliser, crop strategy, human resource management policy, etc., each of which might differentiate their amounts of potential yield.

While the first 2 assumptions are farm-specific, the last one can be "ignored" in a sense by understanding that the unifying component in this entire web is the front-end, customer-facing fast food chain: they deemed that all the farms they source from provide them with ingredients that are indistinguishable from one another, hence why they source from multiple farm companies aross different geographies. How can we use this information to our advantage? This is where it gets interesting.

Methods for Multiple Multivariate Time Series Forecasting¶

(Back to top)

The scale of this problem can get very overwhelming very quickly, but it helps to understand two things: one, the objective is simply per farm, per hour for the year ahead; two, it's not impossible and has been done before by people of much greater mettle than us (at this point in time.) For starters, let's rephrase the problem. Instead of looking at this as an agricultural time series project, let's instead say we have multiple different patient records from a clinic, each with their own time series consisting of biological readings over time (EEG, fMRI, etc.) Suddenly the problem isn't so Byzantine anymore. Let's take another perspective: we have multiple products per category (pens $\in$ stationary $\in$ office products), each product with its own historical demand data. We now need to predict the year-ahead demand for each product. Simple, isn't it? And it's clearer that this problem isn't "new". The way such a problem was dealt with by people much more versed in these matters than ourselves here was, of course, with neural networks - but why? Let's look at a few methods, starting with the most applicable one. Something very important to keep in mind: we are only looking for multivariate solutions, because we want to incorporate weather.

DeepAR: Probabilistic Forecasting with Autoregressive Recurrent Networks¶

(Back to top)

Amazon; David Salinas, Valentin Flunkert, Jan Gasthaus · arXiv:1704.04110
The problem addressed here is that of demand forecasting for multiple different products under multiple different categories, but at a scale which provides an almost power-law distribution of sales vs. items. In more concrete terms, multiple products with different kinds of seasonality, market presence and historical demand all require to be considered, which makes traditional machine learning models and neural nets unfeasible. This Amazon problem also involved multivariate time series per product per category. Relating the approach discussed there to our problem, the proposed solution (which was quite effective) was as follows:

Source: arXiv:1704.04110; page 3, section 2

"At each time step t, the inputs to the network are the covariates $x_{i,t}$, the target value at the previous time step $z_{i,t-1}$, as well as the previous network output $h_{i,t-1}$ . The network output $h_{i,t} = h(h_{i,t-1}, z_{i,t-1}, x_{i,t}, \Theta$) is then used to compute the parameters $\theta_{i,t} = \theta(h_{i,t}, \Theta)$ of the likelihood ($z|\theta$), which is used for training the model parameters. For prediction, the history of the time series $zi,t$ is fed in for $t < t0$ , then in the prediction range (right) for $t >= t_0$ a sample $\hat{z}_{i,t} \approx (\cdot|\theta_{i,t})$ is drawn and fed back for the next point until the end of the prediction range $t = t0 + T$ generating one sample trace." Relating this idea to what we might be able to accomplish, effectively we lag our target by 1 observation and feed that into recurrent neural network's encoder stage. After all the values have been observed by the network, the decoder stage begins predicting in the same lagged fashion. This makes sense because our current farm's yield is not impacted by the weather at this particular instant, it's impacted by the weather the farm's surface experienced some time ago; it also explains what kind architecture we can use and how we feed our data into said architecture, but what about handling the multiple different categories?

Probabilistic Demand Forecasting at Scale¶

(Back to top)

Amazon; Joos-Hendrik Böse, Valentin Flunkert, Jan Gasthaus, Tim Januschowski, Dustin Lange, David Salinas, Sebastian Schelter, Matthias Seeger, Yuyang Wang · Proceedings of the VLDB Endowment, 2017 - Volume 10, Issue 12
The problem discussed here is similar in nature to what was touched upon earlier: multiple products within different categories need to have their demand forecasted for multiple stakeholders of the firm. The question is specifically "what is the probability distribution of the demand of an item for a specific time horizon starting from a date in the future?" which, for our purposes, translates rather well to "what is the probability distribution of the demand of an ingredient, for a specific time horizon, starting from some date in the future?" The way this was tackled was masterful; quoting the paper:
"The demand forecasting problem constitutes in predicting the demand for a group of items at a certain range of days in the future, given demand data for all items up to the present, as well as other input data sources. [...] A sensible requirement of a forecasting system is consistency: the predicted distribution of $Z_{I;(t_L, \delta_1 + \delta_2)}$ should be the same as that of $Z_{I;(t_L, \delta_1)} + Z_{I;(t_L + \delta_1, \delta_2)}$. Moreover, users should be able to query any quantile of the forecast distribution, (e.g., the median or the 90-th percentile) for any combination of lead time and span, as well as any group of items I." Source: DOI 10.14778/3137765.3137775; page 2 (1695), section 2

Specifically, the approach taken was something that's rather unfeasible for us right now given our... humble computing resources compared to what was used in the paper, but it does open up a lot of doors for us: the concept of distributed learning schemes. Quoting the paper again: "there exists a variety of approaches to tackle the forecasting problem: in classical approaches, a single (local) model per item time series is computed. However, in many cases it might be beneficial to employ global learners that consider groups of items." Under local learning, a single model per item is parameterised by the network; in our case this would require 1434 different models per farm - a statement which speaks for itself. Under global learning, a single model for all items is parameterised by the network; in our case, this would entail a single neural network for ~20mn rows of data, which will trash our RAM in an instant. However, the paper then continues: "Local learning with hierarchical regularization. We support an extension to local learning which allows models to share statistical strength between items. The idea is to use a regularizer that shrinks the weight vector towards vectors learned at higher levels, incorporating the weights of many items. Global-local learning. The features as well as the weight vector which parameterizes the model here consist of a global part and a local part. In the case of the parameter vectors, the global part $w$ is shared by all items and local parts $v_i$ are specific to individual items $i$."

Relating this to our current situation, in addition to autoregressing our target variable by a lag of 1 period, we can integrate our knowledge of how our climate behaves: climactic variability is minimal within a geography and therefore, we can assume each farm to already have been clustered. Following through from our discussion of granularity earlier, we can assume each location as a local model while one company is a global model. This way, we train to predict each farm's performance on the basis of its location, monitored and corrected globally on the basis of that farm's company. Practically what this means is we extract our data from the database on the basis of company (select * from <table> where farming_company = <company>;) which occurs in the outer loop and feed that dataset into our global network. Once the epoch completes its training, we extract those weights and build $n\_companies$ number of networks in an inner loop that each take in the Pythonic equivalent of (select * from big_loop where location = <location>;) in terms of data, and receive the pre-trained global weight tensor. The inner epoch finishes and the loops reset themselves until convergence or an early stopping criterion.

A prominent question at this stage is "do we really need all this computational complexity?" After all, universal function approximation is still linear at heart; wouldn't ARIMAX and its family be equally (if not more) effective? Autoregression literally played one of the biggest roles in the first paper. The truth is that while the AR*X family of simple linear models continues to remain very effective at what they do, they do have a few shortcomings about themselves that needed addressing. Now we get to the real wacky parts.

Deep State Space Models for Time Series Forecasting¶

(Back to top)

Amazon; Syama Sundar Rangapuram, Matthias Seeger, Jan Gasthaus, Lorenzo Stella, Yuyang Wang, Tim Januschowski · 32nd Conference on Neural Information Processing Systems, 2018
Deep Space State Models, apart from sounding really Sci-Fi, are actually very simple: the heart of the model is a regular State Space Model (ARIMA/X, Exponentially Smoothed series, Time Delay Embedding, etc.), but its parameters are provided by a recurrent neural network. State space modelling is widely applied to dynamical systems, where the evolution of said system is controlled by non-observable state variables. The system exhibits observable variables which are determined by said "latent" state variables - the SSM models both of them. While this isn't as straightforward as the other linked papers, it does offer insight into how different combinations of classical and deep models can be combined together into something that Just Works$^{TM}$. The training stages however are slightly more involved:

Source: NeurIPS 2018; page 4, section 4

"During training, the inputs to the network are the features $x_{t}^{(i)}$ as well as the previous network output $h_{t-1}$ at each time step t in the training range ${1, 2, \dots, T_i}$. The network output $h_t = h(h^{(i)}_{t-1}, x^{(i)}_t, \phi)$ is then used to compute the parameters of the state space model $\Theta_t$ after mapping it to the corresponding ranges of the parameters. Given the time series observations $z^{(i)}_{1:T}$ in the training range, the likelihood of the state space parameters $\Phi$ (which are functions of the shared network parameters $\phi$) are computed according to Eq. 4. The shared network parameters $\Phi$ are then learned by maximizing the likelihood." What all of this means for us is that our RNN (or LSTM) will simply be trained against an ARIMAX model, such that its $n$ outputs correspond to the parameters required by the space state model. Practically speaking, this would be slightly difficult to achieve and is also rather hard to keep a track of. There is also another issue that we should have noticed keeps recurring with RNNs or LSTMs for time series forecasting: the problem of extremely long sequences destroying differentiability. There are ways around this, however.

Deep Transformer Models for Time Series Forecasting: The Influenza Prevalence Case¶

(Back to top)

Google; Neo Wu, Bradley Green, Xue Ben, Shawn O’Banion · arXiv:2001.08317
This was, perhaps, one of the most influential papers for our decision making process on which model is the most appropriate in terms of computational complexity and required labour. The motivation behind this approach stems from the fact that sequence-aligned models, while natural choices for modelling time series data, are faced with vanishing and exploding gradient problems along with (eventual) limited effectiveness of convolutional filters. More generally said, these methods have limitations in modelling long-term and complex relations in sequential data, and so a different approach is warranted. At the time of this paper, transformers already existed and were known to have overcome a lot of the limitations of recurrent networks, owing to their capability of looking at the entire dataset as a whole. Unlike sequence-aligned models, Transformers do not process data in an ordered sequence, they instead process the entire sequence at once, but with a self-attention mechanism that allows it to learn granular dependencies of the data. It's effectively a combination of an LSTM with an exponential (or weighted) moving average: a winning combination for time series. The transformer itself is rather pale compared to the networks we see today, but for the time it did a phenomenal job - even beating DeepAR! Quoting the paper:

Source: arXiv:2001.08317; page 2, section 1

"Encoder. The encoder is composed of an input layer, a positional encoding layer, and a stack of four identical encoder layers. The input layer maps the input time series data to a vector of dimension dmodel through a fully-connected network. This step is essential for the model to employ a multi-head attention mechanism. Positional encoding with sine and cosine functions is used to encode sequential information in the time series data by element-wise addition of the input vector with a positional encoding vector. The resulting vector is fed into four encoder layers. Each encoder layer consists of two sub-layers: a self-attention sub-layer and a fully-connected feed-forward sub-layer. Each sub-layer is followed by a normalization layer. The encoder produces a $d_{model}$-dimensional vector to feed to the decoder. Decoder. The decoder is also composed of the input layer, four identical decoder layers, and an output layer. The decoder input begins with the last data point of the encoder input. The input layer maps the decoder input to a $d_{model}$-dimensional vector. In addition to the two sub-layers in each encoder layer, the decoder inserts a third sub-layer to apply self-attention mechanisms over the encoder output. Finally, there is an output layer that maps the output of last decoder layer to the target time sequence." The attention mechanism is what allows us to be granular with our data: for our purposes, we could send in an entire location's worth of information as long as it's been positionally encoded, and tell our transformer to pay attention to the last 48 hours of data when predicting the next 24 hours. This kind of model also lends itself extremely well to global learning, while a model like a DSSM would lend itself extremely well to local learning. But of course, the story doesn't stop here, because there are still much harder problems on the horizon. Enter the Temporal Fusion Transformer.

Detour: The Current State of Our Plan¶

(Back to top)

Rahul Singh
We've reached the beans of this entire discussion; the real meat on the bones. Before getting into it, let's address a point that we've been saliently avoiding talking about: the fact that we have categorical data, and farm_ids, in our data. The problem we face is twofold: first, we need to predict a year-ahead amount of data using a year-prior amount of data at the hourly scale; secondly, we need to do this for multiple (1,434) farms. A third, rather non-obvious problem, is that we have categorical data to aid us. If we were to use a traditional network architecture such as an LSTM or a regular Transformer, we can eliminate this problem by understanding that we can encode our specific farm_id with an embedding layer. This also implies that we can embed different categorical variables at the same time, like location. What this would do is it would expand our 10 (or 11) character farm_id into an $n$ dimensional-vector that represents that and only that farm_id in the form of a lookup table (or Python dictionary). Consider the following image from this very well written Hacks For AI article:

Source: Hacks For AI; Adopting Embeddings for Categorical Features (Part 2)

In the image we have 3 categorical features, each with their own $m$ number of levels (or factors). What we do for embedding text is we obtain some seed mathematical representation of it, either through one-hot encoding, or the length of the word, or its frequency (if we're talking about documents), etc., and feed it into an autoencoder style neural network that gives us a latent space representation of that word. In the image, the feature MARRIAGE has 4 levels $0, 1, 2, 3$, each of which can be represented by a vector of values. MARRIAGE therefore is represented by a matrix of $4 \times 5$, where 4 is the number of levels in the feature and 5 is the number of dimensions we have chosen for the vector. During backpropagation, an optimised set of weights for this feature matrix can be learned. After embedding our categorical features, we can simply concatenate their tensors onto our numerical data's tensor and feed the entire chunk into a transformer, starting from the input layer. For a reference idea of how this would work and look, refer to this great article on Deep Learning for Tabular Data Using Pytorch:

Source: Aakanksha NS; Deep Learning for Tabular Data using PyTorch

Now all of this is great so far because not only do we have a way to move past the biggest hurdle staring at us - our categorical data - we also have a network that's just itching to sink its teeth into the vast amounts of data we have to offer it. We can source our data at the corporate level (select * from <table> where farming_company = <company>;) looping over the number of companies we have, and feed that data into a transformer after embedding our categorical features such that we only need to build 6 to 7 different models. Weather interactions and farm behaviour within the purview of a single company is preserved. In order for us to be able to predict per farm while also accounting for global time series nuances (as mentioned earlier under Global Learning), we simply need to sort our train, validation and test sets the same way such that our predictions line up with that farm ID, for that length of series. We can even use our embedding layer's values to determine which farm has received which predictions; we can even assume manual control of the loop and train on every farm available, but test on each farm one by one printing out the farm_id of the current testing farm. However, we also need to keep in mind our GPU constraints: while yes it is a vector processor, it too has only a limited amount of memory that can only hold a certain size of data. In our case, we have only 8GB of VRAM to play with, so any amount of data larger than this could trigger a host of issues that (un)fortunately I have had to deal with each and every one of before (scheduler freezes, page faults, softlocks, complete halts, etc.)

We can do better. While we have dealt with the multivariate nature of our time series already from the days of DeepAR (and also categorical handling), dealing with 1,434 time series that need seeing to is not an easy task by any measure. Additionally, two problems lurk on the horizon, one of which plagues us: one, if we want to query our results similar to what was proposed in Probabilistic Demand Forecasting At Scale, we would need to handle multiple moving pieces (or networks) simultaneously; two, some time series will be of different lengths. Imagine a water supply company having to manage thousands of sensors across their operational geography, each reporting their own time series at different times of the day for a different set of hours only; imagine the amount of data being received by NASA from the James Webb - this time it's not a time series of continuous values, it's a time series of very high resolution images! Enter the Temporal Fusion Transformer.

Temporal Fusion Transformers for Interpretable Multi-horizon Time Series Forecasting¶

(Back to top)

Google; Bryan Lim, Sercan Ö. Arık, Nicolas Loeff, Tomas Pfister · arXiv:1912.09363

What's debatably the most capable time series forecaster so far, the TFT is expressly built for handling temporal complexity of modern, SOTA scales. It's a transformer-type model with attention that combines the best aspects knnown of sequential deep learning, such that it can achieve high performance in multi-step forecasting problems, learn on the fly and provide a very good level of interpretability and introspection. To quote the paper, "[The TFT] specifically incorporates (1) static covariate encoders which encode context vectors for use in other parts of the network, (2) gating mechanisms throughout and sample-dependent variable selection to minimize the contributions of irrelevant inputs, (3) a sequence-to-sequence layer to locally process known and observed inputs, and (4) a temporal self-attention decoder to learn any long-term dependencies present within the dataset. The use of these specialized components also facilitates interpretability; in particular, we show that TFT enables three valuable interpretability use cases: helping users identify (i) globally-important variables for the prediction problem, (ii) persistent temporal patterns, and (iii) significant events."

One of the major driving forces behind deciding to use the TFT for our problem here is the fact that we have multiple different time series at play within an entire dataset that has categorical features which also interact with one-another. Sifting through the large levels of interaction is specifically what the TFT is designed to do, and in a very optimised way that we were keen on incorporating: global-local learning, which although most transformers implement owing to their approach-based approaches, the TFT arguably does better due to its internal dynamics of decoding feature interacions. Another strong driving force behind the decision was the inherent feature selection capabiliies of the TFT that allows us to understand which climate measurement the network thinks is most applicable. All of this architecture can be represented by the following image:

Source: arXiv:1912.09363; page 6, section 4

While it looks like simply a larger version of our original idea of incorporating separate categorical and numerical paths for encoding categoricals, the core building block of the TFT is the Gated Residual Network (GRN), which itself is a very, very small 2-layer NN. Each layer is a dense connection but with specific activation functions: an Exponenial Linear Unit (ELU), and a Gated Linear Unit (GLU). The former is a noise-suppressing, symmetric, non-contractive activation function whilst the latter consists of two 1D convolutional layers; input to the GLU is convolved twice, with one convolution "feature map" being passed through a sigmoid in order to identify salient yet effective features. These GLUs are used heavily across the TFT, mostly within GRNs, which themselves are used all over the TFT and especially within the Variable Selection Networks.

Within the VSN, each feature within the current row is passed through a GRN, yielding a latent representation of itself that can further be manipulated. For example, all features are sent in as $\xi$ and are returned as $\tilde \xi$ after the GRN does its work, however each feature map is also equted to the entirety of the current row via $\Xi$ in order to preserve state ($\xi_{t}^{1} \dots \xi_{t}^{m_{\chi}} = \Xi_{t}$). Also important to notice is that static variables are sent in separately and used to condition the LSTM, VSN and Static Enrichment layers with non-temporal data, such that its effect over time too is accounted for. The static encoders generate 4 vectors, $\{\vec C_h, \vec C_c, \vec C_s, \vec C_e\}$, where $\vec C_h$ and $\vec C_c$ are used to initialise the LSTM hidden and cell states; $\vec C_s$ is sent into that row's VSN, and $\vec C_e$ is forwarded to static enrichment.

The LSTM is your very standard run-of-the-mill temporal encoder that provides the TFT with a temporal understanding of what data its being given. Following this first massive phase of feature selection, multi-head attention ($Multihead(Q, K, V)$) takes over with one slight difference from the regular multi-head attention: the weights across each head are shared to facilitate introspection. Attention is applied to the data and only future inputs are passed forward into the prediction layers on the right, corresponding to LSTM decoder layers.

The crux of all this is twofold: not only does each instance pass through each of these layers (and therefore, not only does the TFT perform variable selection for each instance), but all static, past and future inputs make use of separate variable selection networks. This greatly aids the TFT in understanding the joint impact of static variables with dynamic variables over time; in our case, the interactions between locations (climate), companies (fertilisers and/or crop strategies), and ingredients (raw food sources/materials). The entire feature selection process constitutes the local learning section and is the encoder part of the TFT.

The last, most interesting point is that even coupled with all of this math, the TFT has been known to perform very, very well on small sets of data owing to its feature selection capabilities. That alone allows it to discern very salient relationships within the data given to it that other models need explicitly specified. The key points, therefore, for us to take away are these:

  1. Inherent global-local learning allows the TFT to discern relationships between features we have a hard time sifting through due to the volume of our data.
  2. Involvement of static features with dynamic features in a way that measures their impact over time and across categories (can our company produce differently within a location because of subtle weather differences?).
  3. Ability to work well with small amounts of data and generalise to larger amounts of the same data allows us to avoid full-size TFT computational demands and test its capabilities on a subsampled dataset that's deemed to be representative of the population at large (within reason).

So given all of this context, pretext and history of multidimensional multivariate momentum, we'll be using the TFT for our work going forward. To phrase this in a slightly more accurate fashion, we're not going to sit through and manually understand the dynamics of each farm because we are lazy. We have universal function approximators, we'll use universal function approximators!

Practical Limitations of Forecasting with the Temporal Fusion Transformer¶

(Back to top)

A few important points to note before we begin: we're not implementing the TFT from scratch in PyTorch (even though that would be quite enjoyable), we're instead using an existing implementation in PyTorch Forecasting, which itself depends on PyTorch Lightning. This is necessary to mention because PyTorch Forecasting, in its version as of the time of this writing, has a few small bugs that cause errors during training and need to be fixed manually. These bugs are not structural, they simply exist because PyTorch, Lightning and Forecasting do not update in synchronicity with each other. What follows is the list of files and associated changes that need to be made in order to get this working:

1. PyTorch Forecasting: Encoders Issue (pytorch_forecasting/data/encoders.py)¶

The problem with this file is that Pytorch Forecasting is affected by NumPy's deprecation of np.float, which causes errors most usually encountered from this file. We depend here on this file for our TimeSeriesDataSet. This is an issue I've faced before many times in other packages that depend on np.float, and thus far the workaround - even the suggested one - is the obvious route: go into the file and replace np.float with float. There is also a relevant pull request (#1257) available that shows what's required to be done with the file, however keep in mind this important point about GPUs usually working with 32-bit floats and change only the specific occurrences of np.float.

2. PyTorch Forecasting: Base Model Issue (pytorch_forecsating/models/base_model.py)¶

The problem here actually stems from the return type of the PyTorch-Lightning function get_init_args(), which is defined in the file pytorch_lightning/utilities/parsing.py at line 140. The current version of the Lightning function (as of the time of this writing) returns two items from its local stack as comma-separated values, which we all know by now is achieved by Python using a tuple. Contrast this against the BaseModel class' __init__ method contained in this file, specifically its series of operations between lines 259 and 263. The method initialises its class by inspecting the contents of the given dataset, which itself is governed by the PyTorch dataloader, and at line 260 we can see that the return values of get_init_args() are stored in the variable init_args, which is then iterated over in line 262. The problem here is that the iteration assumes init_args is a dictionary when in fact - at some point during Lightning's lifecycle, when the function return values were updated - it's a tuple. This raises an error because tuples do not have any method like .items(). The solution implemented here was to simply respectively assign the return values from get_init_args() to appropriate variables, giving us this kind of code at line 260 in the PyTorch Forecasting file: _, init_args = get_init_args(frame). The iteration and all its dependencies should proceed normally after this small change.

The next two points have been written completely in retrospect, after encountering some exceedingly frustrating, seriously cryptic errors (in true Python fashion...) when running inference with the TFT, after fully training a model:

3. PyTorch Forecasting: NaNLabelEncoder() Necessity¶

The first issue faced when trying to run inference after training was that we didn't tell our TFT what strategy to use when an unknown category is encountered. This was accomplishd by including the use of the NaNLabelEncoder() within the TimeSeriesDataSet initialisation for train data, as discussed here at SO: PyTorch Forecasting Unknown Category Encountered. Why was this not in the Forecasting documentation?

4. PyTorch Forecasting: Target Presence within Test¶

A rather interesting second inferential issue was that - for some mysterious reason - instantiating a prediction TimeSeriesDataSet, or even just trying to predict with the TFT on unseen data, required the target feature to exist. The workaround is placing a target feature in the Pandas DataFrame but filling it with zeroes. Note that the dummy target feature was first initialised with regular zeroes, i.e. 0. This caused a large hue and cry from PyTorch because it demanded float values. The workaround finally used then is initialising the dummy target vector with 0.0; it's also possible to initialise it with 0 and then cast it to a float using .astype(). If using the latter option, be sure to assign the return value of .astype() to a dataframe: the function is not an inplace operation!

There is a corresponding GitHub issue (PyTorch Forecasting #1264; Colab Notebook also available) for these issues.

Data Extraction and Modelling¶

(Back to top)

Now with that all of that out of the way, let's discuss how we're going to feed this behemoth of a neural network enough data to keep it satiated. The standard PyTorch approach to feeding a network is through a DataLoader, which is simply a Python object that returns a single row from an underlying Dataset, which itself is an object that simply implements a __getitem() method. This is so that each time the loader is subscripted in a loop like loader[i] for i in 1..10, a single "row" from the underlying dataset is retrieved. The concept and utility behind this is absolute astounding because it allows the programmer to implement any kind of behind-the-scenes fetch logic regardless of whether the data is in memory, on disk, or in a database. As long as a single row is provided when the method is called, the model using that data source will happily train itself.

The standard DataLoader, as mentioned relies on an underlying Dataset which obviously implies the data is batched and ready to be iterated over. The Dataset also is required to have a __len__() method that informs the dataloader of the length of the underlying dataset. Given this kind of functionality, it seems trivial to structure our dataset and loader using our database: when our dataloder is indexed, our dataset's __getitem()__ method queries our database for batch_size number of rows. In fact, this way the data might never even have to touch our RAM.

But not so fast! Since we're using PyTorch Forecasting's implementation of the TFT, we have a few conveniences and a few hindrances ahead of us: addressing the hindrances, Forecasting and its ecosystem revolves around the TimeSeriesDataSet class which works best (and is recommended to use with) a Pandas DataFrame. This is because of the ease and familiarity of the Pandas ecosystem with a lot of use-cases: it's much, much easier to point out what's what using a DataFrame from the front, and also manipulate it from the back. Because of this, our data is forced to enter memory and reside within a DataFrame, though we can reduce this amount tremendously by incorporating a functional programming approach. We are also therefore limited - in terms of how fluid flow out of a bottle is limited by the neck - to approaching Forecasting's ecosystem through the TimeSeriesDataSet, which might not suit all of our data ingestion needs.

Hindrances aside, the TSDS does offer us some massive conveniences for handling our data, owing to its Pandas backend: we do not need to manually encode, embed, scale, transform or otherwise preprocess our data at all. We just point out to the TSDS what we want done to what features, and it'll do its job getting it ready for the model we want to use. The TSDS also comes with its own methods for creating its own DataLoader, as well as instantiating the model we're using from its metadata! Because of these provisions by the TSDS, we'll be using it to batch our data and get it ready for the model.

The question then is how do we give our data to the TSDS? Since we have the drive speeds and lightweight access to our database, the best option we have for batching data is to iterate over it, as described earlier. The difference is this time instead of having a DataLoader iterate over our database for us, we manually pull out what we want from the db and give it to a TSDS, which will reside in memory and feed our model data with its own dataloader. This is where having an index on our tables comes in tremendous help.

GPU Limitations¶

(Back to top)

There are a few very real limitations we need to be aware of before training our model, almost all of which com from experimenting with the TFT multiple times before this final versioni: though a vector processor at heart, our GPU is a rasterisation device and therefore does not excel at general-purpose compute tasks; it's specialty is drawing things on a screen. This means that it can crunch numbers very quickly, but it can't store a large amount of information on itself nor can it crunch numbers that quickly. This gives us another problem: how much data can we fit on the thing? Empirically tested again over multiple different experimental rounds, our results - while promising - do not exactly inspire a lot of confidence: as mentioned, we do have a vector processor to play with, but it isn't oriented for GPGP. Adding onto this constraint is the fact that the TFT itself is rather large with a minimum of ~10,000 parameters. This situation greatly narrows down our options, leaving us with potentially only one best solution: we "batch" our data from the database by farm, where each farm should have a maximum expected amount of ~8,780 rows for one ingredient produced, and then give that dataset to the TSDS object which will further batch it onto the GPU from memory. Very, very far from ideal, but we still get to incorporate the TFT for a problem very apt for it, and we play within the bounds set by Forecasting.

The next obvious question is: how do we complete going over all the farms? As it stands, hot-swapping the underlying dataset while a model is running whilst keeping its dataloader in tact - all through Forecasting's API - is very much possible, but also a bit too much. Instead, thankfully, we have an extremely brilliant way out of this: Once the TFT completes training on the current TSDS, we'll leverage the brilliant mechanism offered by Lightning to save our model along with all of its parameters so far in a checkpoint file. We will then fetch the next batch of data from the database, provide it to the TSDS constructor and reload the model so that it continue training with the new batch of data. Keep in mind that while this approach is possible, it's extremely far from ideal: the best way to go about this would be to simply create a dataloader that executes an SQL fetch query when indexed, which spits out a batch_size number of rows which the model directly ingests.

The other small problem of pulling data from databases in order to feed it to a GPU is usually read/write speed: as mentioned, the computer involved has an Astra KD350X 256GB NVMe drive with read-write speeds of 3.4GB/s (3400MB/s, 425MT/s). For reference, the RAM installed on this machine has a maximum peak rating of 26GB/s (25600MB/s, 3200MT/s). The maximal size of the largest table in the database doesn't even cross 3GB, which literally means our entire dataset can be transfered in a second to the GPU (if the entire amount of data is given complete access to the device without any models or forward/backward pass functions, tensors, program states, memory maps and pages, etc.) The point is that access speeds are not a limiting factor in this scenario.

GPU Training Speeds¶

(Back to top)

This section coincides with part 8 of the associated SQL script.

The (hopefully) final limiting factor to how much data we can give our GPU: besides the fact that we're batching over an entire farm and our dataset consists of multiple farms, each with their own different states of production, we're also limited by the fact that our device is a rasterisation device. In more concrete terms, training the TFT on one farm's performance for 3 quarters of the year, for one epoch, takes around 7 minutes. We have 1,434 farms to deal with, which means training over our entire dataset with the ideal amount of 5 epochs would take $1434 \times 7 \times 5 = 50190$ minutes, or $\frac{50190}{60} = 836$ hours, or $\frac{836}{24} = 35$ days.

But all isn't lost, for there is opportunity in every problem: owing to the kind of data we have, we can exploit its repetitive structure over time and create a much smaller, more representative and "generalisable" subsampled dataset that we can safely train on whilst still retaining as much variability of state and feature interactivity as possible, in terms of both categorical and numerical features. Once we have enough information for our trained model this way - because essentially what we want to capture are the dynamic complexities over time - we can simply keep bootstrapping the best TFT onto more and more training data, rather than goiong through it all at once. We'll be back here as soon as we're ready to train. For monitoring our GPU, the 3rd party tool UMR by Tom St. Denis was used, which is a common userspace debugging and diagnostic tool for AMD GPUs using the AMDGPU kernel driver via PCI express. For now, it's back to the database.

Training the TFT¶

(Back to top)

We're back after subsampling our dataset into a smaller version of itself that we argue is representative of the population to a sufficient degree, whilst also satisfying the constraint of training time. As a post script to this idea, our objective with training time was to limit it to 24 continuous hours, maximum. The current subsampled dataset has an estimated train time of ~13 continuous hours at an individual farm speed of 7 minutes, over 110 farms out of 1,434. The criteria for selecting the farms were that they have to have a complete time series (8,784 datapoints, $366 \times 24$), and they had to satisfy a sudoku puzzle: they have to come from different locations that their parent company spans, and they need to produce one unique ingredient. More details on this rationale can be found in the accompanying SQL script file for this project as well as the associated spreadsheet.

This section will proceed into actually training the TFT on our beloved little GPU. As stated, our approach is a functional one and intends to extract one farm at a time from our source (subsampled) dataset residing in our PostgreSQL database, feed it into a TimeSeriesDataSet object and let that handle giving data to our GPU. Once a dataset is exhausted, i.e. training completes for that farm, we save our best performing model as a Lightning checkpoint, reinstantiate our TSDS, reload the model from said checkpoint and continue training with the new batch of data. This is accomplished through the humble for loop.

Utility Functions: Data Fetch¶

(Back to top)

These functions will be the ones we use when querying our database, feeding that data into the TimeSeriesDataSet class constructor, and initialising a DataLoader from the TSDS. A small point to note is that for some inexplicable reason, Pandas has a hard time inferring what kind of datatypes are being returned when we fetch data from our PostgreSQL connector. Because of this, we need to manually cast our column's data to their appropriate types before returning the dataframe. A lot of the TemporalFusionTransformer related code, especially that for the TimeSeriesDataSet is adapted right from the Forecasting tutorial available at PyTorch Forecasting Tutorial: Demand Forecasting with the Temporal Fusion Transformer.

def fetch_train_data(cur, fid, ing, source):
    cur.execute(f"""
    select *
    from {source}
    where farm_id = '{fid}'
    and ingredient_type = '{ing}';
    """)

    tmp_df = pd.DataFrame(
        cur.fetchall(),
        columns = [d[0] for d in cur.description]
    ).astype({
        "quarter"               : "int",
        "month"                 : "int",
        "week"                  : "int",
        "day"                   : "int",
        "dow"                   : "int",
        "hour"                  : "int",
        "time_idx"              : "int",

def get_tsdsets(dframe, s_cats, kn_reals):
    day = 24
    month = 31 * day
    quarter = 3 * month

    # minimum lookback: 2 weeks; maximum lookback: 3 quarters
    # minimum predict: 1 week; maximum predict: 1 quarter
    min_encoder_len = 14 * day
    max_encoder_len = 3 * quarter
    min_predict_len = 7 * day
    max_predict_len = 1 * quarter

    training_cutoff = dframe["time_idx"].max() - max_predict_len
    train_tsd = TimeSeriesDataSet(
        dframe[lambda x: x.time_idx <= training_cutoff],
        time_idx                   = "time_idx",
        target                     = "yield",
        group_ids                  = ["group"],
        min_encoder_length         = min_encoder_len,
        max_encoder_length         = max_encoder_len,
        min_prediction_length      = min_predict_len,
        max_prediction_length      = max_predict_len,
        static_categoricals        = s_cats,
        time_varying_known_reals   = kn_reals,
        time_varying_unknown_reals = ["yield"],
        allow_missing_timesteps    = True,
        target_normalizer          = GroupNormalizer(
            groups = ["group"],
            transformation = "softplus"
        ),
        categorical_encoders       = {
            "group"                : NaNLabelEncoder(add_nan = True),
            "farm_id"              : NaNLabelEncoder(add_nan = True),
            "deidentified_location": NaNLabelEncoder(add_nan = True),
            "ingredient_type"      : NaNLabelEncoder(add_nan = True),
            "farming_company"      : NaNLabelEncoder(add_nan = True)
        }
    )

    valid_tsd = TimeSeriesDataSet.from_dataset(
        train_tsd, dframe, predict = True, stop_randomization = True
    )

    return (train_tsd, valid_tsd)
In [4]:
def mkloaders(train_df, valid_df, batch, workers):
    train_dl = train_df.to_dataloader(
        batch_size = batch,
        train = True,
        num_workers = workers,
        pin_memory = True,
    )

    valid_dl = valid_df.to_dataloader(
        batch_size = batch,
        train = False,
        num_workers = workers,
        pin_memory = True,
    )

    return (train_dl, valid_dl)

Utility Functions: Model Initialisation¶

(Back to top)

These functions are called to build the TFT from a given source TSDS, as well as initialise a Lightning Trainer object. The Trainer is a wonderful piece of code that seamlessly manages the entire training loop cycle of a PyTorch model. All the Trainer ingests is the model to train and a couple of dataloaders to keep the model training. There is a lot of customisability available through the use of certain flags; all of which can be found at the documentation page for the Lightning Trainer API. For our purposes, here we're telling the trainer that we want it to offload our model to our GPU, that we have 1 GPU available, to summarise our model before training (which we'll see is contained in a giant error-red box), to clip gradients at a value lower than 0.1, and most importantly: to resume training of our model from any given checkpoint path. The build_tft function is where we're setting up our Temporal Fusion Transformer on the basis of the TSDS we're building at an earlier stage. Most of the flags for the TFT are set appropriately by the TSDS and then copied over or pointed to. Due to computational complexity, the size of the model is the bare minimum allowed by the Forecasting implementation.

Originally we also included an Early Stopping function get_earlystop_cb() which we passed to our trainer to effect early stopping on our model. Since we're training with only 1 epoch per farm, we don't want early stopping because the farms coming in after ES kicks in won't be trained on. The callback itelf was the standard, run of the mill Early Stopping logic, also present within the Forecasting TFT tutorial.

In [5]:
def get_trainer(epochs, save_path = None):
    return pl.Trainer(
        accelerator = 'gpu',
        enable_model_summary = True,
        devices = 1,
        gradient_clip_val = 0.1,
        max_epochs = epochs,
        resume_from_checkpoint = save_path
    )
In [6]:
def build_tft(temporal_dframe):
    return TemporalFusionTransformer.from_dataset(
        temporal_dframe,
        attention_head_size = 1,
        dropout = 0.1,
        hidden_size = 8,
        learning_rate = 0.03,
        loss = RMSE(),
        optimizer = "adam",
        output_size = 1
    )

Utility Functions: Model Inspection¶

(Back to top)

The last batch of helper functions we have are those for inspecting the performance of our model. Once training is done, the TFT as implemented in Forecasting has the capability of automatically plotting out its performance against the validation set of data. Also included are plots that show us which features what part of the model thinks is most important. While this functionality is relatively rudimentary compared to what was envisaged in the paper, it still is quite convenient and insightful to see how the TFT actually works in practice. As a part of the plotting functions, each plot is saved to a file in the current working directory.

In [7]:
def plot_preds(tftrans, valid_dl):
    raw_predictions, x = tftrans.predict(
        valid_dl, mode = "raw", return_x = True
    )

    return best_tft.plot_prediction(
        x, raw_predictions, idx = 0, add_loss_to_title = True
    );
In [8]:
def plot_feats(tftrans, valid_dl):
    raw_predictions, x = tftrans.predict(
        valid_dl, mode = "raw", return_x = True
    )
    interpretation = tftrans.interpret_output(
        raw_predictions, reduction = "sum"
    )
    return tftrans.plot_interpretation(interpretation)

Setup: Database Loop¶

(Back to top)

This is the penultimate step before we begin looping over our database and training our model. Here we initialise containers for the features we know are categorical and don't vary with time, and the features we know are continuous and that do vary with time. These features will also be known in the future, which means the TFT can depend on the existence of values for these features when predicting for unseen data as well. There are other options available too such as temporally changing unknown continuous features for which values change with time and are not known in the future, and categorical features that also change with time, like branch location or colour of a star.

We also initialise containers that will hold our future incoming scores of performance, a convenience variable that holds the name of our source table in the database, and most importantly: the list of farms in the table that we'll be iterating over. On the basis of the current active ingredient, we'll fetch the farms that are applicable and train on them.

TFT Training Loop¶

(Back to top)

And this is finally where we set our TFT to train on the data we're giving it. There is a very, very large elephant in the room that needs addressing: earlier we had mentioned that the TFT finishes training on a farm in approximately 7 minutes, which we said was for one epoch. Even after subsampling our data, we still are faced with time constraints that cannot be overcome, and so we've chosen exactly 1 epoch to train with. Something should be said here: This is not the first pass at training the TFT. There have been at least 8 prior runs at training, each in a different combination in order to test which one will maximise efficacy without taking too long. In more concrete words, training began on the 21st of February; this version was only arrived at after running the TFT for long enough during the previous attempts such that various other methodological and technical errors arose. The other side of the coin here is that a single forward pass through the data, even for just a single epoch, has only so far - from all previous test runs of the model, of which there were quite a few - generated a maximum RMSE of ~2500 with the average being around 150, which is rather acceptable and as well should be, because one of the many advantages of the TFT is that it can discern nuanced behaviour well from small sets of data.

26Feb23 Note: we're continuing after a GPU segfault that occurred at around 1h 18m of training, after completing around 8 farms out of 14 in the first out of 4 ingredients. This is why the output might seem truncated.

In [11]:
# we need to iterate only over those farms that are present for that ingredient
cur.execute(f"select distinct ingredient_type from {source_table};")
ingreds = list(itertools.chain(*cur.fetchall()))

# 26Feb23 - since we had a segfault and we're resuming, we need to be sure we
# aren't resuming training from farm #1 all over again. The farms that have
# already been trained on can be ignored, which we're doing in our modified
# query here. We're not storing a separate variable like `not_list` and keeping
# our forbidden farm IDs in there because formatting lists in the middle of a
# multiline string is slightly out of the question for a list of only 8 farms.
# Maybe if the list grows bigger we'll do that,
for ing in ingreds:
    cur.execute(f"""
        select distinct farm_id
        from {source_table}
        where ingredient_type = '{ing}'
        and farm_id not in (
            'fid_101039', 'fid_101271', 'fid_104740', 'fid_105593',
            'fid_118325', 'fid_119338', 'fid_119518', 'fid_120597'
        );
    """)
    farms = list(itertools.chain(*cur.fetchall()))

    for fid in farms:
        # get the data feed ready
        train_tsds, valid_tsds = get_tsdsets(
            fetch_train_data(cur, fid, ing, source_table),
            static_categoricals, temporal_known_reals
        )
        train_dl, valid_dl = mkloaders(train_tsds, valid_tsds, 16, 8)

        # build the model based off the data feed
        trainer = get_trainer(epox, save_path)
        tftrans = build_tft(train_tsds)

        # train the model (implicit cuda)
        trainer.fit(
            tftrans,
            train_dataloaders = train_dl,
            val_dataloaders = valid_dl
        )

        # save the best performer for the next iteration
        save_path = trainer.checkpoint_callback.best_model_path
        best_tft = tftrans.load_from_checkpoint(save_path)

        # evaluate performance
        plot_preds(tftrans, valid_dl).savefig(f"plots/{ing}_{fid}_preds.jpg")
        for (title, ax) in plot_feats(tftrans, valid_dl).items():
            ax.savefig(f"plots/{ing}_{fid}_{title}.jpg")
        plt.close("all")

        # flavour text; extend epoch size to continue training
        print(f"completed training for farm {fid}.")
        epox += 1

    print(f"\n---------- ingredient {ing} completed. ----------\n")

Forecasting with the TFT¶

(Back to top)

The way we go about using the big mean TFT we trained is similar: we pull out the data we want to predict on, in this case each farm from the predict dataset, structure a TimeSeriesDataSet around it by bootstrapping the initialiser with our existing TSDS, initialise its dataloader and feed it to the Lightning Trainer. We need to keep in mind however that we intend on predicting for one quarter at a time within the confines of a single farm (producing a single ingredient, i.e. maximum length of 8,760 rows), so either we inform our dataloader to spit out data in batches of 4 over the entire year, or we structure our own dataloader and attempt to use that. As discussed however, the format of the data for Forecasting models matters, so we should be better off using the TSDS.

In order for running inference with the TFT to work, it's crucial that points 3 and 4 here have been taken into consideration. Most importantly, categorical features that are known to have factors that the model might not have been exposed to during training need to have corresponding NaNLabelEncoder() functions assigned to them.

Utility Function: Test Data Fetch¶

(Back to top)

Why didn't we club this with our previous fetch function? Because the prediction set doesn't have the target column and therefore we would have had to use some specialised logic to get that sorted out which could affect function execution times even though the query is the same. Offloading the query into the calling function (or cell) gets very messy and unreadable and is prone to errors if we want to update something in our query. The tradeoff of a function like this taking up extra stack space is acceptable given the conveniences we get from not only having the function, but also having two separate ones that explicitly force the programmer to state their intention: am I fetching train or test?

In [10]:
def fetch_test_data(cur, fid, ing, source):
    cur.execute(f"""
    select *
    from {source}
    where farm_id = '{fid}'
    and ingredient_type = '{ing}';
    """)

    tmp_df = pd.DataFrame(
        cur.fetchall(),
        columns = [d[0] for d in cur.description]
    ).astype({
        "quarter"               : "int",
        "month"                 : "int",
        "week"                  : "int",
        "day"                   : "int",
        "dow"                   : "int",
        "hour"                  : "int",
        "time_idx"              : "int",
        "group"                 : "int",
        "farm_id"               : "category",
        "id"                    : "int",
        "ingredient_type"       : "category",
        "farm_area"             : "float",
        "farming_company"       : "category",
        "deidentified_location" : "category",
        "temp_obs"              : "float",
        "cloudiness"            : "float",
        "wind_direction"        : "float",
        "dew_temp"              : "float",
        "pressure_sea_level"    : "float",
        "precipitation"         : "float",
        "wind_speed"            : "float"
    })

    return tmp_df

What we're going to do here is try to predict for one farm first. If everything goes well, we'll automate the process and iterate over every farm in test in a fashion not dissimilar to what we've already done for train. Again, owing to PyTorch's capabilities of saving models, we simply need to load our model from its checkpoint (after instantiating all associated objects) and give it some data to run its forward pass on. Simple, right?

# very, very important that this is a float value, lest we want PyTorch Core
# issues regarding tensor data types when running inference.
tmp_df["yield"] = 0.0

day = 24
month = 31 * day
quarter = 3 * month
max_predict_len = 1 * quarter

# also important that we use the exact same lengths we gave when training
# because we have leap years and different quarters within a dataset (i.e. one
# farm can have quarters like 1 -> 2 -> 3 -> 4 -> 1). This also helps when
# comparing prediction length and dataset length. See debug notebook for more.
train_cut = tmp_df["time_idx"].max() - max_predict_len
pred_df = tmp_df[lambda x: x.time_idx >= train_cut]
print(pred_df.dtypes)

2568 rows × 21 columns

...why exactly are we supposed to be predicting for a number of rows that's indivisible by $365 \times 24 = 8760$? It's not even a leap year thing because we're off by $\frac{336}{24} = 14$ days or 2 exact weeks. What gives?

27Feb23 Post Script: it eluded us at the time, but the reason we're off by two weeks is most likely because of our minimum encoder length specification of two weeks. We're asking our model to encode at minimum two weeks, maximum 9 months, so for somehow - for some reason - it's taken a total duration of $(24_h \times 14_d) + (24_h \times 31_d \times 9_m) = 336 + 6696 = 7032$ for encoding and $(24_h \times 14_d) + (24_h \times 31_d \times 3_m) = 336 + 2232 = 2568$ for decoding. A potential solution here is setting our minimum encoding length of 0 so that we get exact cuts of 9 months of training and 3 months of validation/prediction.

Prediction Loop¶

(Back to top)

The objective now is to receive a prediction for each row of our test dataset, which consists of exactly one full year of data ($365 \times 24 = 8760$ rows) for all the farm's we've seen so far. Our model is going to predict one quarter at a time (2568 rows, or $\frac{2568}{24} = 107$) days at a time, and so we need $\frac{8760}{2568} = 3.411$ batches of predictions for one farm, which should look strange. Additionally, our model is going to give us predictions of length 2232, which is exactly 93 days, or 1 quarter, or 3 exact months assuming $3 \times 31$ days in a month. How are we going to reconcile these two? We're going to do it in the most straightforward way possible (for now):

  1. pull a farm's data from the database into a Pandas DataFrame and append a dummy yield column onto it, filled with 0.0.
  2. store our id column separately because we'll need that to identify which row associates with which prediction.
  3. send in batches of 2,568 rows at a time for prediction, collecting 2,232 rows in return. This is done for 3 iterations because 3.411 is not a whole number.

What about the final 1,056 rows? We'll just reverse-slice the DataFrame starting from the last index and moving backwards until we have 2568 rows to send in. We can't pad everything with zeroes because our model is extremely type-safe and will happily return errors if our categorical features are not categories, amongst other problems. In more concrete terms, we can calculate a final reverse index split of -2064, because since we're sending in batches of 2568 but getting out batches of 2232, we need a way to have only 8760 with the least amount of temporal overlap. We simply multiply our output size by the number of iterations we send in batches of 2568, and subtract the number of outputs we have so far from the number we need (8760). In other words:

$batch\_in = 2568, batch\_out = 2232, input\_size = 8760$
$\implies \frac{8760}{2568} = 3.411 iters$
$\implies (batch\_out \times \lfloor 3.411 \rfloor) - input\_size = final\_select$
$\implies (2232 \times 3) - 8760 = 2064$

The same approach will work for our differently sized farm tables if we just change the input size (aka the size of the dataframe coming in from the database, in number of rows). The following is a MCVE of what we want to accomplish (in C; the Python implementation is left as an exercise to the reader :). ):

uint16_t batch_in = 2568;
uint16_t batch_out = 2232;
uint16_t sizes[6] = {8760, 17520, 26280, 35040, 43800, 52560};

for (uint8_t i = 0; i < 6; i++) {
        uint16_t input_df_size = sizes[i];
        uint8_t iters = (int)(input_df_size / batch_in);
        uint32_t final_select = (batch_out * iters) - input_df_size;
        printf("input_df_size = %d\tfinal_select = %d\n", input_df_size, -final_select);
}
return 0;

$> ./sizes
