Note that there are around ~15 farms that have duplicate entries, i.e. they have $8760 \times 2 = 17,520$ rows. No data is different within their rows, they simply have different IDs and can't be grouped together. We'll handle them separately. Finally, this approach is seriously far from ideal: with a little more careful planning, it's easily possible to align our training, validation and prediction time slices and datasets so that we don't need to juggle all of this. Unfortunately, time is short, so we're going to wing it.

De-duplicating Test Farms¶

(Back to top)

This section coincides with the prologue section of the associated SQL script.

Now that most of our regular farms are taken care of, let's move onto dealing with ones in dup_farm_list. Going through their information in the database shows that they have duplicated rows with exactly the same values, but different IDs for every single row. For instance, the first two rows of one of the farms have the exact same climate measurements and timestamps, but the id value is different. This makes grouping and ordering them a little tricky, which in turn makes getting our time_idx correct even tricker. For a glimpse at what we're dealing with (formatting for aesthetics sake):

So what can we do here? Well, if all the values are precisely the same across duplicated rows, we should be getting the same prediction for both rows. In other words, if our model is working correctly, our problem should take care of itself. However, the problem of different ids for each row makes sorting this batch, either in Python or SQL, rather difficult since it would involve some pretty hefty windowing functions. This is an issue because when we're assigning our time_idx to these farms' rows, we need to do so in a way that matches the actual timestamp. If we want to separate our two overlapping series by ordering them separately, such that we have two proper sets of series stacked one on top of the other where the first one goes from 00:00:00 to 23:00:00, followed by the second one restarting from 00:00:00 and ending at its own 23:00:00, we need some unique way to do it; some way to ensure we get something like:

date farm_id ingredient id ... temp cloud wdir dewpt pressure precip wspd
2017-01-01 00:00:00 fid_122174 ing_w 26740355 ... -5.6 4 230 -10.6 1010.0 0.233 3.6
2017-01-01 01:00:00 fid_122174 ing_w 26740780 ... -6.1 4 190 -10.6 1009.7 0.000 3.1
2017-01-01 02:00:00 fid_122174 ing_w 26740973 ... -5.0 4 210 -10.0 1009.4 0.000 4.1

2017-01-01 02:00:00 fid_122174 ing_w 26741089 ... -5.0 4 210 -10.0 1009.4 0.000 4.1

Looking closely, we should notice that we already had to solve this kind of problem once before: when coming up with time_idx. What we need is a column vector that assigns a unique within-repetition (aka within-group) number to each repeating timestamp, but a repeating number to each without-group timestamp. In more concrete terms, we can do something like this:

Which means now if we want a kind of "tiled" sort, we can get one and we no longer need to worry about duplicated entries: one time series of 8760 rows will be a complete one without any overlapping timestamps. We can then proceed as almost usual because we still need to repeat predicting for one farm n_repetitions times. We can do this by simply getting the number of distinct group_idxs we have for that farm and iterating over them in a 3rd nested loop. This also avoids us having to rewrite our reverse-indexing logic we used in the first run of predictions by shifting the burden of data organisation to the database.

Now the question is: how do we actually execute this sort? Do we create a new database table with our organised information and an index for fast retrieval, or do we create a view within the database without an index, or do we initialise a Psycopg2 transaction and use a temporary table with an index? The first option consumes disk space, the second option could be slow, the third option would require us to very carefully execute our instructions lest we want to rollback in the middle of the loop. As it stands, the database backup archive is already 12.8GB in size with every table and view we have so far, including table indices. Post-script: after trying different methods, it appears the most effective solution is creating another table in database along with an index. As mentioned earlier, the associated SQL script and rationale is fully documented in the accompanying SQL file for this project.

        "dew_temp"              : "float",
        "pressure_sea_level"    : "float",
        "precipitation"         : "float",
        "wind_speed"            : "float"
    })

    return tmp_df

Final Predictions Merge¶

(Back to top)

Before we conclude, there is one thing left for us to do: we need to merge both our prediction CSVs into one giant file. We'll do that using possibly one of the best tools for the job: AWK, because there's really no reason for us to be doing this kind of operation in Python. The shell can handle this just fine, and it's also quicker than importing everything into Python and performing it in memory. We'll be using AWK the same way as recommended here on SO (Concatenate N number of CSV Files into one) and here on Baeldung (CSV file merging). In short:

$> awk '(NR == 1) || (FNR > 1)' preds_v1.csv preds_v2.csv > preds_final.csv

Where the logical operators ensure that our headers are not duplicated. And with this final operation, our project is officially fully complete.

Concluding Thoughts¶

(Back to top)

Going through each of the saved plots we have of train-vs-validation (in ./plots/*) here would take an enormous amount of time, so instead we'll summarise our findings: the TFT's multifaceted gateway architecture and powerful feature selection routines proved to be quite effective in terms of detecting salient behaviour amongst the farms it trained on. In almost every case, seasonality and trend were preserved quite well during validation, with the forecasted patterns fitting in nicely with the established prior series. In some situations it's also very evident that the TFT's noise suppression mechanisms did their job, suppressing spurious spikes and noisy swings in the time series to yield a concise, tight and dense set of forecasts.

Even in terms of feature importances, the TFT recognised that some locations work together and was able to use the same feature repeatedly for that location, whilst using different features for other locations. Obviously, the weather feature we all expected to influence farm yields the most was also weighted the highest by the TFT: temperature. However, it's very clear that the model's performance is nowhere near as adequate as it can be, which is simply an artefact of the design of our training methodology. But when this is viewed with respect to the rather severe hardware limitations we had, it definitely holds its worth!

Not only was such an enormous model capable of being trained on a humble rasterisation device, it also took an amount of time per epoch that other models of this size and complexity simply wouldn't be able to match. Working through the mathematics of the TFT is also rather straightforward, which is a great nod towards the amount of thought that went into designing the architecture. Additionally, what's important to note here is with just a single training epoch per farm on extremely limited accelerator hardware (in the grand scheme of general-purpose compute), the TFT was able to identify nuances in the data given to it that otherwise would definitely have been missed by other models like DeepAR or DSSMs. As the icing on the cake, all of this was learned from a heavily restricted amount of data to maximise training variance on whatever constrained hardware we had. That alone is possibly the biggest redeeming factor for choosing to use a TFT for this kind of problem: quite certainly, given more time, if we refine our approach we would have a model capable of chewing through this vast amount of data with ease.

So was this project a success? Personally, I would say definitely so; and I would go a step further to say that this is something I would 100% love to do again!

Future Scope and Recommendations¶

(Back to top)

Of course, while this entire experience has been quite an interesting and enjoyable one, we would be remiss if we didn't summarise what we identified as pain points that, with a little work, can be subdued in the future. For starters, and quite possibly the biggest bottleneck we faced - even with regards to forecasting - is the approach we took of feeding data into our model. Given the time constraints of the project, using the TimeSeriesDataSet was the most convenient approach (and was quite an effective one given the capabilities of the TSDS). However, the utility of that class' API is, at the time of this writing, rather questionable in the face of large volumes of data that cannot fit in memory or need to be handled in a fashion other than batching. The second recommended course of action would be performing a little bit of extra EDA, with the intention of diving into the data a little more than we did here.

Iterable Streaming Dataset¶

(Back to top)

The current idea of using a TSDS for the model, as enabling as it is, is also rather equally limiting owing to the assumption that the current workflow suits all. Of course this wasn't the intention of Forecasting, for the whole point is to remain extensible; nevertheless, the documentation itself states that Forecasting by default expects the use of the TSDS. For proof of concept, let's think about what's happening when our TSDS is exhausted: we're saving our model, loading in a new Pandas DataFrame, giving it to the TSDS constructor and then reloading the model and continuing training. As mentioned, the most ideal approach would be to stream data directly in from the database as and when it's required by the GPU in batch_size chunks. PyTorch Lightning enables us to do so using the very powerful and versatile IterableDataset class.

Unlike batch-style Datasets that implement __getitem()__, producing a single row on demand from a pre-defined amount of data they hold, IterableDatasets represent a stream of data that can be as long as necessary. This object implements __iter()__ and __next()__ methods that yield batch_size number of rows when called. This approach alone makes it infinitely easier to cycle through our database fetching batch_size rows to feed into the GPU; we can even do this with a server-side cursor such that there is minimal amount of data touching memory. Consider the following class, where we use exactly that method (the server-side database cursor):

  • self.cur.itersize limits our "window": it says how many rows to load into the client (Python) from the server at a time. Psycopg2 will fetch itersize rows to the client at a time. Once the for loop exhausts that batch, it will fetch the next one.
  • limit 10, which we had earlier, says "collect only 10 rows from the query". When our itersize is less than limit, we'll be loading the client with 5 batches of rows at a time. Once the for loop yielding those number of rows in the batch exhausts itself, the next 5 are loaded into the client from the server and yielded for reading.
  • islice(iter_load, 15) takes an iterable object and returns a segment from it, between the elements defined by the start and end arguments given to the function. The default single-integer style function call we're using here signifies the phrase "end at 15 iterations." We're saying "cycle through our dataloader giving us 15 rows", which means first the query is executed server side and 10 rows are prepared, then 5 rows are loaded into the client for viewing, and because we've requested 15 we'll get the first 5. After those 5 are returned, the next 5 from the server are loaded into the client and shown to us. After that, nothing happens because the query is done. For real kicks, try islice(iter_load, 5, 10): we'll get only the hours from 5 to 9.

All of that was before we added in cycle_query(self) and pointed our __iter__() function to cycle_query() instead of to query_db(). What cycle() does is it creates an infinite iterator, so when we reach the end of an epoch we loop back around to the start. This guarantees consistent batch sizes and avoids having to implement any file-end logic. In other words, while without cycle we would end fetching rows after the 10th one was returned, with cycle we simply loop back around and start collecting the 10 rows from the beginning all over again. Now, the number of times we do this is governed purely by islice(), which means we just set the number of rows to be fetched equal to the amount of data that can be held in our GPU, and we're in business! The only thing in our way then is initialising the TFT and transforming our data into tensors and/or categorical embeddings, which - given enough time - is a walk in the park with PyTorch!

Sources:

  • PyTorch Lightning: Managing Data
  • PyTorch: IterableDataset
  • SO: Psycopg2 Uses Up Memory on a Large SELECT Query
  • James McCaffrey; VisualStudioMagazine: How to Create a Streaming DataLoader for PyTorch
  • David MacLeod; Medium: How to Build a Streaming Dataloader with PyTorch

class FarmIterable(torch.utils.data.IterableDataset):
    def __init__(self, pq_connector, table, batch):
        self.con = pq_connector
        self.cur = self.con.cursor(name = "batch_cursor")
        self.cur.itersize = batch
        self.table = table

    def query_db(self):
        # try without limit
        cur.execute(f"""
            select
                "quarter"::int, "month"::int, "week"::int, "day"::int,
                "dow"::int, "hour"::int, "time_idx", "group", "farm_id",
                "ingredient_type", "farm_area", "deidentified_location",
                "temp_obs", "cloudiness", "wind_direction", "dew_temp",
                "pressure_sea_level", "precipitation", "wind_speed",
                "yield"
            from {self.table};
        """)
        for row in cur:
            yield row

    def cycle_query(self):
        return cycle(self.query_db())

    def __iter__(self):
        return self.cycle_query()

Time Series Dissection: Clustering, Classification, Seasonality and Outlier Detection¶

(Back to top)

THe informed decision we took during imputing our data, that farms of the same location should behave similarly, was empirically verified by looking at the amount of variability within a location. This was done rather primitively: by simply looking at the amount of unique values reported from each location for certain measurements in relation to the total number values for that location. The rationale was that if 19 farms from location A report hourly, every day, such that they have 8,784 records at the end of a year, but they also only report 27 distinct values of temperature throughout the year, it means that the temperature throughout the year varies only by $\frac{27}{8784} = 0.30\%$ for the entire year. Conversely if those farms report 5,874 unique values for wind direction within the year, it means that almost every day has a new and different direction for the wind giving us a variability of $~67\%$. Our overall measurement of climactic variability is included in the associated spreadsheet for this project; the calculation was performed in SQL and results exported.

However while this seemed to be a decent approach, it wasn't deeply verified. The going idea here is to employ a clustering algorithm that's specifically desinged for working with time series, such as Dynamic Time Warping, Longest Common Subsequences, Fourier Transformations, SVD, Independent Component Analysis, etc.; and verify whether the number of clusters we receive are in consonance with the number of locations we have, within a certain margin of error. This way, we can be certain that farms of the same location behave in a similar fashion owing to the impact of climate, and it would also answer another assumption of our work so far: that corporations are not as dissimilar as they seem to be, because even though they might use different cropping techniques or fertilisers for better yields, their strategy is still dependent on the environment and therefore their differentiation is limited.

Dynamic Time Warping¶

(Back to top)

At it's core, what DTW does is best explained in relation to the approach taken by standard Euclidean clustering. Euclidean distances on a time series dataset measure the distance between each data point occurring at that time; in other words, if we have two time series A and B with row indices $i\dots n$, then Euclidean distances would only measure $\sqrt{(A_i - B_i)^2}$. In contrast, Dynamic Time Warping calculates an "optimal match" between two given time series with certain restrictions:

  • Every index from the first sequence must be matched with one or more indices from the other sequence, and vice-versa
  • The first index from the first sequence must be matched with the first index from the other sequence (but it does not have to be its only match)
  • The last index from the first sequence must be matched with the last index from the other sequence (but it does not have to be its only match)
  • The mapping of the indices from the first sequence to indices from the other sequence must be monotonically increasing, and vice versa, i.e. if $j > i$ are indices from the first sequence, then there must not be two indices $l > k$ in the other sequence, such that index $i$ is matched with index $l$ and index $j$ is matched with index $k$, or vice-versa. In ot her words, you cannot have a point in time from A, say at time $t = 7$ match with a point from B that's at $t = 9$ while A at $t = 8$ matches with B at $t = 6$. You cannot have crossing "lines".

The "optimal match" is the one that satisfies all restrictions with the minimal cost, where the cost is computed as the sum of absolute differences (i.e. $\sum{|A_i - B_i|}$), for each matched pair of indices, between their values. Such computation also lends itself well to being aware of the different phases of the involved series. This approach is perhaps best explained with a picture, neatly depicted by Heka.AI in their very effective article on Time Series Clustering:

Source: Heka.ai: Time Series Clustering

In fact, DTW has been used across financial applications in order to deterministically model behaviour that's superficially chaotic to good results. Clustering our farms together would not only have shown us whether our idea of locations behaving similarly is indeed true, it also would have allowed us to more confidently subsample our dataset such that we pick $n$ farms that best represent their cluster, for which again we could use DTW on the farm of choice against the average temporal behaviour of the cluster. Additionally, like many other clustering approaches, it would help us identify farms that are outliers on top of other powerful temporal anomaly detection algorithms.

Longest Common Subsequences¶

(Back to top)

Another flexible method of time series clustering that adapts well to noisy series and is also "multivariate" is the LCS, which when given two sequences X and Z, says that Z is a subsequence of X if removing some elements from X produces Z. Quite simple and straightforward, and can be adapted to multivariate comparisons such as comparing X, Y and Z together to find a common subsequence. The longest subsequence between X and Z is the longest common subsequence: $nLCS = \frac{length(LCS)}{\sqrt{m \cdot n}}$. To find the longest subsequences common to $X_i$ and $Y_j$, compare the elements $x_i$ and $y_j$. If they are equal, then the sequence $LCS(X_{i-1}; Y_{j-1})$ is extended by that element, $x_i$. If they are not equal, then the longer of the two sequences, $LCS(X_i; Y_{j-1})$ /, and $LCS(X_{i-1}; Y_j)$ /, is retained. (If they are both the same length, but not identical, then both are retained.) However, the LCS is a dynamic algorithm and therefore is not particularly efficient.

Singular Value Similarity¶

(Back to top)

Specially proposed in Outlier Detection for Temporal Data by Gupta et. al. which is quoted here because the explanation is just too juicy: "Consider two multi-variate time series $M_a$ and $M_b$. Let the time series be defined over time intervals of length $l_1$ and $l_2$ , respectively. Thus, the multi-variate time series can be represented using matrices $M_{a}^{l_1 \times c}$ and $M_{b}^{l_2 \times c}$ respectively, where $c$ is the number of metric variables. For both the matrices, we can compute the top $k$ principal components (that can capture $>95%$ variance) to obtain smaller subspaces $P^{c \times k}$ and $Q^{c \times k}$, respectively. Similarity between the two multi-variate time series can be expressed in terms of the similarity between their principal components as the average sum of squares of the cosines of the angles between each principal component in $P$ and $Q$." This can even be adapted to a weighted average which shows the amount of variance explained by each principal component, and is probably the easiest algorithm out of the ones discussed so far.

Seasonality¶

(Back to top)

The methods discussed thus far, if implemented, would make the data going into our TFT much cleaner and easier to handle, not to mention smaller and therefore quicker to chew through. Another common analytical approach for time series is using a simple Fourier decomposition across all of our series to determine if we have a seasonal effect or not:

Source: Sławomir_Biały; Wikipedia Commons, Fourier Transform

Internally the TFT does perform something similar, but we don't need an especially complex algorithm to run on a GPU when we have something much simpler, and that can also detect multiple seasonal effects within a series. In fact, most of the methods here can be combined, for example we can cluster farms together and run inference to verify whether the clustering algorithm has retained some of the constituent's farms most important (largest Fourier values) seasonal effects such that it best represents the behaviour of the cluster or not.
